Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas told a session of the UN General Assembly on Thursday that he would break all agreements with Israel if the country's future government tries to fulfill Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement to annex occupied Palestinian lands.
"If the future Israeli government that is formed proceeds to implement this plan, we will annul all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made," he said.
"We will reject the whole plan completely and completely," Abbas threatened emphatically.
"It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means – no matter what the consequences may be – by fully committing ourselves to working for the application of international law and in the fight against terrorism," declared the Palestinian Authority president, who has already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, the outgoing prime minister of Israel, was again tasked with forming a government after the September 17 elections.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won, he would declare the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to incorporate all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank into Israel.
In the early 90s. Israel and the Palestinians, then led by Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements sponsored by the United States.
Abbas, 84, also promised to hold general elections on Palestinian lands during a session of the UN General Assembly.
The last one took place in 2006.
"Upon my return, I will call local elections in the West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community," the Palestinian president solemnly declared.
In his speech, Abbas also defended the right of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the UN, to exercise the rights of "full members of the UN and all its organs and institutions."
The Palestinian leader concluded his speech by calling on the international community to "force Israel to comply with the United Nations in full respect."
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas's speech, declaring that the Palestinian leader "prefers to focus at the UN on Palestinian Authority efforts against Israel rather than fight against calls for terrorism in the PA under his leadership."
Danon, as the agencies note, did not refer to Netanyahu's announced annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
