PLN 105 million for companies from the video game industry from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
On Friday, the National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the third edition of the GameINN program.
Among the almost 30 projects supported by NCBR, there was, m.in. development of a platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine creating a map of the real world along with an application enabling data transmission by users; a test and training platform for verification of practical skills at the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes, using an innovative gameplay model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the concept of industry 4.0 – according to the NCBR release sent to PAP on Friday.
The aim of the GameINN sectoral program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish sector of video game producers on the global market by 2023.
According to NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% annually.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 is PLN 2.23 billion.
"A specially prepared GameINN research agenda and support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral program, already reaching PLN 300 million, are a significant impulse for further, dynamic growth of Polish gamedev," reads the press release.
The video games industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs focusing on innovation, such as R+D discounts, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by NCBR drive the innovative activity of companies and allow them to compete more effectively in a very competitive market," says Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the release.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project co-financing, but also stays in their pockets – three-quarters of more entrepreneurs benefited from the R+D relief in 2018 than a year earlier.
"The amount of deducted costs related to R+D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in over PLN 300 million in savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by NCBR in three editions of GameINN", emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
Wojciech Kamieniecki, PhD, Eng., Director of the NCBR, reminds that in the two previous competitions, 78 innovative projects were awarded with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million.
The huge interest in the third competition and the variety of submitted applications show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"We are particularly pleased that among the selected projects – as in previous editions – there are projects related not only to entertainment, but also to industry 4.0," he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million.
NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of co-financing of approx. PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million in funding.
Detailed information about the results of the III GameINN competition is available on the ncbr.gov.pl website.
The GameINN sectoral program is implemented as part of the Smart Growth Operational Program.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated in the Polish Games Agreement, which includes, m.in such companies as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
