UBS: The zloty is close to the equilibrium point
"The euro exchange rate will remain around the 4.35 PLN level in the coming months, accompanied by a weak situation in global markets," said Michael Bolliger of UBS Wealth Management.
"Expectations of maintaining a solid pace of economic growth and stable monetary policy speak in favor of stabilizing the zloty's quotations at the current level," the specialist said in an interview with Bankier.pl.
In his opinion, despite clear inflationary pressure, the Monetary Policy Council will not decide to raise rates in an environment in which the vast majority of central banks ease policy.
"While the zloty is properly valued – the euro quotations should remain around the level of PLN 4.35 in the coming months – Polish bonds are not very attractive in his opinion.
Emerging market bonds offer much more favourable yields than Polish securities," said Michael Bolliger, head of asset allocation for emerging markets at UBS Wealth Management.
According to the specialist, the main threat to the Polish economy is the global economic downturn.
"The global slowdown may deepen, but there should be no severe recession, or at most a fall in GDP growth slightly below zero," says Michael Bolliger.
"Investors should underweight global equities, which could be hurt by the lack of prospects for a resolution to the US-China trade conflict and other geopolitical risks, including the impeachment of Donald Trump and Brexit.
Among equity markets, Europe should be relatively the weakest," according to a new letter to investors by UBS Wealth Management chief executive Mark Haefele.
"Eurozone equities should behave worse than US equities because they are more vulnerable amid heightened global trade uncertainty and fears of a slowdown," the document said.
According to Michael Bolliger, after the bull market in the bond markets of the safest countries pushed the yields of German 10-year bonds even to minus 0.74%, it is still possible to deepen the decline in yields.
However, in the longer term, yields on long-term securities should no longer fall, but only short-term ones, due to the easing of banks' monetary policy.
