"42% of the tree species that make up Europe's forest stand are under threat," warns the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in its Red List of European Trees published on Friday.
At the top of the list are m.in chestnut and mountain ash.
IUCN, an organization based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered European tree species for the first time.
It was prepared by specialists who, based on research, came to the conclusion that out of 454 tree species found in Europe (as well as in other places of the world), 42% are "highly endangered".
Among the reasons for the Red Book, the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change are the causes.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
As for the typical European stand, according to IUCN specialists, 58 percent of species are threatened, and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are threatened with extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red List mentions errors in the exploitation of tree stands, accelerated urbanisation, excessive felling of trees, followed by forest fires and changes in the European ecosystem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also strongly threatened.
"The consequences of human activity are leading to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and are putting Europe at risk of extinction of important and undervalued varieties that underpin Europe's ecosystems and affect the health of our planet," concluded the report by Luc Bas, who heads the IUCN European office.
