GUS: Life in Poland is getting better
The report on household budgets published on Friday by the Central Statistical Office shows that it assessed its financial situation as good or rather good last year. as many as 44 percent of them.
A year earlier, this percentage was 37.2 per cent, in 2016 it was 33.5 per cent, and earlier – since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of the situation of households – it has never exceeded 30 per cent.
Last year, it considered its financial situation to be bad or rather bad. A total of 8.1% of households, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and over 20% in 2009.
The best is the financial situation of the households of the self-employed.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the other extreme are pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18 percent.
The subjective assessment of the financial situation of households is also strongly influenced by the number of children.
Single parents are the worst off, of whom 32% declare a good or rather good financial situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households it is 48.8 percent.
In these statistics, the effect of the 500+ program is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016), single parents and large families (with at least three children) assessed their worst financial situation.
The improvement of subjective assessments of the financial situation of Poles is a reflection of a rapid increase in income, primarily from work.
However, this is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good is increasing faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of voivodships, there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are formulated by the inhabitants of the Opolskie Voivodeship, where 48.9% of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
Next are Lubuskie (47.7%), Śląskie (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and Zachodniopomorskie (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opole, disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to last year. less than 94 per cent of the national average, and in Lubuskie 98 per cent.
The highest incomes were recorded by residents of Mazowieckie (120 per cent of the national average) and Silesia (104 per cent).
On average, in Poland, disposable income per person in 2018 amounted to PLN 1693.
In real terms (after adjusting for the impact of price changes) it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, this result is quite low.
In 2016, per capita income increased by 7 per cent, and a year later by 6.3 per cent.
While revenue growth is slowing, it is also slowing down spending growth.
Those per capita amounted to last year. PLN 1187, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% in real terms, and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Surveys of household budgets suggest that the statistical household now spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80%, and by 2006 it was above 90%.
