British MPs have voted against a three-day recess of the House of Commons for the Conservative Party's annual policy conference, as requested by the government.
289 MEPs voted in favour and 306 against.
Normally, the House of Commons does not sit during party conferences, so that MPs do not have to resign from either party conferences or parliamentary sessions.
However, the opposition parties decided that at such a crucial time as the last weeks before the planned exit of Great Britain from the European Union on October 31, the parliament should not interrupt its session.
The government's request for a break was supported by 289 MPs, 306 were against.
Two opposition parties after the conventions
The lack of consent to the recess may be perceived as a political revenge of the opposition against Prime Minister Boris Johnson for his decision to suspend parliament for five weeks (on Tuesday the decision was declared illegal and null and void by the Supreme Court) and for the fact that after the judges' ruling he does not want to apologize for it.
Following the ruling, the House of Commons resumed its session on Wednesday, with the highlight of the day being Johnson's speech and the ensuing heated debate.
Johnson accused the opposition of blocking Brexit and avoiding early elections.
"It's time to deliver Brexit.
It must be implemented in order to respect the result of the referendum.
Brexit must come so that we can deal with an agreement on citizens' priorities, on health care, on the cost of living.
Brexit must be delivered so that we can unite this country," Johnson said.
The Conservative Party conference is due to start in Manchester next Sunday and run until Wednesday 2 October.
Conferences of the two main opposition parties – the Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats – have already taken place.
One of the justifications given by Johnson to explain such a long suspension of parliament was party conferences.
