"Rzeczpospolita": Ignoring a police officer's order will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregarding the order of a certain behavior issued by a police officer is to be a new type of offense, punishable by a fine, arrest or restriction of liberty.
Police trade unionists want to introduce such a change.
The idea went to the Sejm Committee on Petitions.
"The case is serious, because already every year more than half a million misdemeanor cases go to Polish courts," we read.
"Rzeczpospolita" determined that the petition that the Independent Police Trade Union writes to MPs regarding the amendment of the Code of Misdemeanors has a chance of success.
The authors of the petition propose a new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Petty Offences.
It would read: "Whoever does not comply with the request or order of a public official, issued within the limits and on the basis of the provisions of the Act, shall be punished with arrest, fine or restriction of liberty."
"Paragraph 3 of this provision provides for an identical penalty for those who, by disobeying orders, prevent or hinder the performance of an official activity," the daily reports.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski told "Rzeczpospolita" that although he agrees with the main message of the proposed regulation, he fears that if implemented, it could be used in matters of political demonstrations.
"In situations of freedom demonstrations, this would be disadvantageous and instead of easing the situation, it would even exacerbate it," he adds.
According to the statistics provided by the newspaper, 86% of citizens positively assessed police interventions in 2018 and that every month the services undertake 1.5 million interventions in the city.
Buras worries about Europe
Jáchym Topol has writing in his blood.
Among his ancestors are editors, translators, writers.
His father, Josef Topol, was one of the most important post-war Czech playwrights, today mentioned in a row with Václav Havel.
Therefore, from the very beginning there was a curse of talent hanging over Jáchy, which he tries to use.
After eight years, he returned with "Sensitive Man".
The protagonists are Buras and Soňa with their two sons, who, however, do not form a typical Czech family.
They are itinerant actors, they travel around Europe.
He is a lover of Shakespeare and a thief, she is a one-eyed translator who does not part with a bottle of wine.
One of the boys from birth did not make a sound, and for the other time stopped in infancy.
But it is not the heroes who are the most important in this story.
All of them are only a background to observe the world, in which there is no place for artistic nomads.
It is a world of flea-clogged provinces, a society of old, suspicious people and promiscuous youth.
"Sensitive Man" sometimes turns into an absurd theater.
The narrative imitates didaskalia, and the conversations of the characters create this world.
The stage is a Europe full of fears about its future, but also constant questions about the past.
Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancels 105 flights due to Thomas Cook's bankruptcy
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has collapsed, its Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is functioning.
However, the company has problems.
Brussels Airlines announced that it would cancel 105 flights in October due to problems related to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All trips with the office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to get a refund.
The court in Ghent also declared three Belgian subsidiaries bankrupt: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, about 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, Thomas Cook Belgium spokeswoman Leen Segers said the company was now "fully operational" despite the bankruptcy of the British parent company, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office reassured then that customers who bought trips there would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – declared bankruptcy on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The immediate cause of the bankruptcy was the collapse of last-chance talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
Creditors demanded that in addition to the £900m rescue plan already agreed in August, the company should raise an additional £200m as collateral for the winter period, when travel agencies tend to have lower turnover.
However, the company's problems have been growing for several years, resulting in a debt of up to 1.6 billion pounds.
