Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for feedback
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an unusual offer has been prepared for newcomers by the German Görlitz.
The activities are to help in the fight against the progressive decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Görlitz is Germany's easternmost city.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, as The Guardian writes, the city is struggling with significant problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a permanent loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which translated into a 25% decline in the city's population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000 people.
In order to fight depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been submitted to the program.
Two-thirds of them were submitted by residents of large cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom were also interested in the program.
"When we applied, we thought the programme was to convince people to move to Görlitz," said one of the project participants.
"Now we feel like it doesn't matter if we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the average in the whole country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main goal of the program is to get feedback from program participants.
The information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need and, if they decide to move, what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild, who is responsible for the program.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents by offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals to live and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the American Tulsa in the state of Oklahoma.
